
[1]chimney

   CHIMNEY, n.

   1. In architecture, a body of brick or stone, erected in a building,
   containing a funnel or funnels, to convey smoke, and other volatile
   matter through the roof, from the hearth or fire-place, where fuel is
   burnt. This body of materials is sometimes called a stack of chimneys,
   especially when it contains two or more funnels, or passages.

   2. A fireplace; the lower part of the body of brick or stone which
   confines and conveys smoke.
